23. He found affairs in his province, which included Cilicia, Pamphylia, Pisidia, Isauria, Lycaonia, and Cyprus, in a most unpromising condition. From without, a descent of the Parthians was threatened,⁴ which he must resist with a most inadequate force of only two legions, which were scattered· throughout the province and demoralized by mutiny and the inefficiency oi their officers.‘ The condition oi the provincials was still more disheartening. Appius Claudius, Cicero’s predecessor, had practically turned over the provinces to Roman publicani and usurerS,⁶ among the latter of whom M. Brutus figured conspicuously. From the outset Cicero set himself to work to remedy this state of things!
